@eddgrs9193
Yes, ray tracing will be widely implemented until they don't. Ray Tracing will walk the same path as PhysX, G-Sync, Gameworks, Hairworks, Surround, and other Nvidia proprietary tech.

AMD will  form coalition with many other companies to create an alternative, make it open source and free (albeit not as good). So nobody ever bother to implement ray tracing in their games. At least not without Nvidia active contribution, that'll cost them time and money.

@eddgrs9193 Indiana Jones makes the 9070 XT look good. Its 15% slower than the 5070 TI, which is easily balanced out with lower MSRP and even moreso with lower real pricing. So even current 'normal' and optimized RT games are basically evened out between Green and Red, no advantage anymore. 

Obviously the AMD GPU sucks at Path Tracing, but thats not relevant for the future. I say that because a) PT is made up by Nvidia and follows no real standard, and thus AMD/Intel GPUs dont know how to deal with it. And b) the vast majority of Nvidia users has GPUs too weak to use Path Tracing, even the 5070 TI is below 60fps in 1440p+DLSS with most games. So if >95% or so of users cant ust PT, then developers wont care much about it.

PT is mainly relevant if you spend >$1000 for your GPU and dont care about high fps-gaming, which is a tiny niche. Even then it affects very few games and has no gameplay benefit, its just lighting.

